 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Vignette for Cao et al., 2017\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook will show you how to work with the C. elegans L2-stage sci-RNA-seq data from Cao et al., 2017. \n",
    "<br> It aims to cover the following use cases:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Accessing the raw data\n",
    "1. Exploring the expression pattern of a gene of interest\n",
    "1. Finding differentially expressed genes between subsets of cells\n",
    "1. Re-clustering subsets of the data using t-SNE\n",
    "\n",
    "You'll need the R packages listed below.\n",
    "\n",
    "This vignette was written using Monocle version 2.3.5, which is the version that was used for the paper. The source code of Monocle 2.3.5 is provided as a supplementary data file for the paper. You can install it using the command:\n",
    "\n",
    "`R CMD INSTALL monocle_2.3.5.tar.gz`\n",
    "\n",
    "Later versions of Monocle may produce different results for use case 4 (re-clustering with t-SNE) due to changes in how we preprocess the data before running t-SNE. We will update this vignette when we release the next version of Monocle, 2.6.0, to support the new version."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "suppressPackageStartupMessages({\n",
    "    library(dplyr)\n",
    "    library(ggplot2)\n",
    "    library(monocle)\n",
    "})"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "- cds is a Monocle CellDataSet object containing the single cell RNA-seq data from the main L2-stage C. elegans experiment described in Cao et al., along with annotations.\n",
    "- cds.neurons is a re-clustered subset of the neuronal cells from cds.\n",
    "- cds.experiment.2 has data from the second C. elegans experiment described in Cao et al.. This includes intestine cells that were missed in the first experiment, but the data overall is lower quality than the first experiment. In the manuscript, we only included the intestine cells from this experiment and excluded the rest."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Use case 1: accessing the raw data\n",
    "\n",
    "The raw gene-by-cell UMI (unique molecular identifier) count matrix for a CellDataSet can be accessed using the `exprs` function. It is stored as a sparse matrix object (\"`.`\" = 0)\n",
    "\n",
    "Note that if you need \"even rawer\" data (FASTQ files), they are available at the Gene Expression Omnibus (www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/geo) under accession code GSE98561.\n",
    "\n",
    "If you aren't familiar with working with single cell RNA-seq data, we highly recommend that you take a look at the examples and utility functions presented in the other sections of this document instead of trying to dive in to the raw data directly."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "3 x 3 sparse Matrix of class \"dgCMatrix\"\n",

       "WBGene00000001                       .                       .\n",
       "WBGene00000002                       .                       .\n",
       "WBGene00000003                       .                       .\n",

       "WBGene00000002                       .\n",
       "WBGene00000003                       ."
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},

   ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The `pData` function is used to access cell annotations.\n",
    "- n.umi is the number of unique molecular identifiers observed to be expressed by a given cell.\n",
    "- Size_Factor is n.umi divided by the media n.umi across all cells.\n",
    "- tsne_1 and tsne_2 are the coordinates for the cell in the t-SNE dimensionality reduction.\n",
    "- Cluster is the id of the t-SNE cluster the cell is part of (defined by density peak clustering).\n",
    "- cell.type and tissue are the annotations that we used throughout the analysis of Cao et al."
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Use case 2: exploring the expression pattern of a gene of interest\n",
    "\n",
    "The `show.expr.info` function returns statistics related to the expression of a given gene in tabular form. The first argument is the gene name. The second argument specifies whether to show statistics at the level of tissues, cell types, or neuron (sub)-types. See the examples below.\n",
    "\n",
    "The function returns a data frame with five columns:\n",
    "- facet -- the tissue / cell type / neuron type\n",
    "- tpm -- the expression of the given gene in the facet in TPM (transcripts per million).\n",
    "- prop.cells.expr -- the proportion of cells in the facet that express at least one UMI (unique molecular identifier) for the given gene. Note that cells in different facets can have very different average number of UMIs per cell, so TPM is the better measure of relative expression.\n",
    "- n.umi -- the number of UMIs (unique molecular identifiers) observed for the given gene in the facet. This is the \"sample size\" from which the TPM value is computed.\n",
    "- total.n.umi.for.facet -- the total number of UMIs observed across all genes for all cells in the facet.\n",
    "\n",
    "Note that low levels of expression of a given gene in cell types you would not expect may be due to leakage of RNA in the fixed cells. For this experiment, based on the expression patterns for a few marker genes, we estimate that the background level of expression you will observe randomly in cells that do not truly express a given gene is ~1-2% of the expression of the highest-expressing cell type."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/html": [

       "<tbody>\n",
       "\t<tr><td>Body wall muscle</td><td>7972.27222      </td><td>0.96451347      </td><td>157028          </td><td>19390434        </td></tr>\n",

       "\\begin{tabular}{r|lllll}\n",
       " facet & tpm & prop.cells.expr & n.umi & total.n.umi.for.facet\\\\\n",
       "\\hline\n",

      "text/html": [
       "<pre class=language-r><code>function (gene, expr.info) \n",
       "{\n",
       "<span style=white-space:pre-wrap>    if (class(expr.info) == \"character\") {</span>\n",
       "<span style=white-space:pre-wrap>        expr.info = gsub(\"[.]\", \" \", tolower(expr.info))</span>\n",
       "<span style=white-space:pre-wrap>        if (expr.info == \"tissue\") </span>\n",
       "<span style=white-space:pre-wrap>            expr.info = tissue.expr.info</span>\n",
       "<span style=white-space:pre-wrap>        else if (expr.info == \"cell type\") </span>\n",
       "<span style=white-space:pre-wrap>            expr.info = cell.type.expr.info</span>\n",
       "<span style=white-space:pre-wrap>        else if (expr.info == \"neuron type\") </span>\n",
       "<span style=white-space:pre-wrap>            expr.info = neuron.type.expr.info</span>\n",
       "<span style=white-space:pre-wrap>    }</span>\n",
       "<span style=white-space:pre-wrap>    gene.id = get.gene.id(gene, fData.df = expr.info$gene.annotations)</span>\n",
       "<span style=white-space:pre-wrap>    data.frame(facet = names(expr.info$tpm[gene.id, ]), tpm = expr.info$tpm[gene.id, </span>\n",
       "<span style=white-space:pre-wrap>        ], prop.cells.expr = expr.info$prop.cells.expr[gene.id, </span>\n",
       "<span style=white-space:pre-wrap>        ], n.umi = expr.info$n.umi[gene.id, ], total.n.umi.for.facet = expr.info$total.n.umi.for.facet) %&gt;% </span>\n",
       "<span style=white-space:pre-wrap>        arrange(-tpm)</span>\n",
       "}</code></pre>"
      ],
      "text/latex": [
       "\\begin{minted}{r}\n",
       "function (gene, expr.info) \n",
       "\\{\n",
       "    if (class(expr.info) == \"character\") \\{\n",
       "        expr.info = gsub(\"{[}.{]}\", \" \", tolower(expr.info))\n",
       "        if (expr.info == \"tissue\") \n",
       "            expr.info = tissue.expr.info\n",
       "        else if (expr.info == \"cell type\") \n",
       "            expr.info = cell.type.expr.info\n",
       "        else if (expr.info == \"neuron type\") \n",
       "            expr.info = neuron.type.expr.info\n",
       "    \\}\n",
       "    gene.id = get.gene.id(gene, fData.df = expr.info\\$gene.annotations)\n",
       "    data.frame(facet = names(expr.info\\$tpm{[}gene.id, {]}), tpm = expr.info\\$tpm{[}gene.id, \n",

       "        {]}, n.umi = expr.info\\$n.umi{[}gene.id, {]}, total.n.umi.for.facet = expr.info\\$total.n.umi.for.facet) \\%>\\% \n",
       "        arrange(-tpm)\n",

      "text/markdown": [
       "```r\n",
       "function (gene, expr.info) \n",
       "{\n",
       "    if (class(expr.info) == \"character\") {\n",
       "        expr.info = gsub(\"[.]\", \" \", tolower(expr.info))\n",
       "        if (expr.info == \"tissue\") \n",
       "            expr.info = tissue.expr.info\n",
       "        else if (expr.info == \"cell type\") \n",
       "            expr.info = cell.type.expr.info\n",
       "        else if (expr.info == \"neuron type\") \n",
       "            expr.info = neuron.type.expr.info\n",
       "    }\n",
       "    gene.id = get.gene.id(gene, fData.df = expr.info$gene.annotations)\n",
       "    data.frame(facet = names(expr.info$tpm[gene.id, ]), tpm = expr.info$tpm[gene.id, \n",
       "        ], prop.cells.expr = expr.info$prop.cells.expr[gene.id, \n",
       "        ], n.umi = expr.info$n.umi[gene.id, ], total.n.umi.for.facet = expr.info$total.n.umi.for.facet) %>% \n",
       "        arrange(-tpm)\n",
       "}\n",
       "```"
      ],
      "text/plain": [
       "function(gene, expr.info) {\n",
       "    if (class(expr.info) == \"character\") {\n",
       "        expr.info = gsub(\"[.]\", \" \", tolower(expr.info))\n",
       "        if (expr.info == \"tissue\")\n",
       "            expr.info = tissue.expr.info\n",
       "        else if (expr.info == \"cell type\")\n",
       "            expr.info = cell.type.expr.info\n",
       "        else if (expr.info == \"neuron type\")\n",
       "            expr.info = neuron.type.expr.info\n",
       "    }\n",
       "    \n",
       "    gene.id = get.gene.id(gene, fData.df = expr.info$gene.annotations)\n",
       "    data.frame(\n",
       "        facet = names(expr.info$tpm[gene.id,]),\n",
       "        tpm = expr.info$tpm[gene.id,],\n",
       "        prop.cells.expr = expr.info$prop.cells.expr[gene.id,],\n",
       "        n.umi = expr.info$n.umi[gene.id,],\n",
       "        total.n.umi.for.facet = expr.info$total.n.umi.for.facet) %>%\n",
       "    arrange(-tpm)\n",
       "}"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "show.expr.info"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The `plot.expr` function can be used to highlight cells that express a given gene on the t-SNE map.\n",
    "- Cells that do not express the gene will be colored grey. They are made semi-transparent so as to better highlight the cells that do express the gene.\n",
    "- Cells that express the gene will be colored according to their cell type. The top 4 highest-expressing cell types will be assigned distinct colors. Other cell types will be lumped together.\n",
    "- Cells in the \"Failed QC\" category are those that express the gene, but are excluded from the analysis due to either having an unusually low UMI count or being a likely doublet."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },

   "cell_type": "markdown",

   "source": [
    "### Use case 3: testing for differential expression between subsets of cells\n",
    "\n",
    "We've defined a function `two.set.differential.gene.test` that finds and reports statistics on differentially expressed genes (DEG) that distinguish between two defined sets of cells. This is a wrapper that just adds a bit of functionality around Monocle's `differentialGeneTest` function.\n",
    "\n",
    "`two.set.differential.gene.test` takes four arguments:\n",
    "1. cds -- a CellDataSet object that includes both sets of cells you wish to compare\n",
    "1. set.1.filter -- a boolean vector of length ncol(cds) indicating which cells should be in Set 1\n",
    "1. set.2.filter -- a boolean vector of length ncol(cds) indicating which cells should be in Set 2\n",
    "1. formal -- if TRUE, p-values and q-values are computed for differential gene expression and genes are ranked by q-value. if FALSE, no formal statistical test is performed and genes are heuristically ranked. formal = F makes the function run much, much faster.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Warning**: if you run `two.set.differential.gene.test` on large sets of cells (>10000-ish), it may take a bunch of memory.\n",
    "\n",
    "The utility functions `is.tissue`, `is.cell.type`, and `is.neuron.type` may be used to create the boolean vectors required for the `set.1.filter` and `set.2.filter` parameters. Each function takes a CellDataSet and a string and tests for each cell whether its tissue / cell type / neuron type is defined (not NA) and equal to the given value."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,

    {
     "name": "stderr",

   ],
   "source": [
    "ASEL.vs.ASER.DEG = two.set.differential.gene.test(\n",
    "    cds.neurons, is.neuron.type(cds.neurons, \"ASEL\"), is.neuron.type(cds.neurons, \"ASER\"))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "`two.set.differential.gene.test` returns the following statistics:\n",
    "- set.1.umi -- the number of UMI (unique molecular identifiers) observed for the gene in Set 1\n",
    "- set.2.umi -- the number of UMI (unique molecular identifiers) observed for the gene in Set 2\n",
    "- set.1.tpm -- gene expression in Set 1 in TPM (transcripts per million)\n",
    "- set.2.tpm -- gene expression in Set 2 in TPM (transcripts per million)\n",
    "- higher.expr -- which set has higher expression (TPM)\n",
    "- log2.ratio -- log2(TPM of higher expressing set / (TPM of lower expressing set + 1))\n",
    "- precision -- (# of cells expressing gene in higher expressing set) / (total # of cells expressing gene)\n",
    "- recall -- (# of cells expressing gene in higher expressing set) / (total # of cells in higher expressing set)\n",
    "- f.score -- geometric mean of precision and recall. genes are sorted by this metric"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },

    "Running `two.set.differential.gene.test` with `formal = T` will compute q-values (the false detection rate at which a gene can be considered to be differentially expressed between the two sets). This is very slow however, so we recommend not using it for exploratory analysis and only using it after you've found something interesting and want to verify that the finding is statistically robust."
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "*tni-3* is a troponin that is expressed in body wall muscle (BWM) in the head, but not in the posterior.\n",
    "<br>*cwn-1* and *egl-20* are Wnt ligands that are expressed in posterior BWM, but not anterior BWM.\n",
    "<br>Using these genes as markers, let's look for differentially expressed genes between anterior and posterior BWM."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 30,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "# of cells in set 1: 1254\n",
      "# of cells in set 2: 1290\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "BWM.anterior.vs.posterior.DEG = two.set.differential.gene.test(\n",
    "    cds,\n",
    "    is.cell.type(cds, \"Body wall muscle\") & expresses.gene(cds, \"tni-3\"),\n",
    "    is.cell.type(cds, \"Body wall muscle\") & (expresses.gene(cds, \"cwn-1\") | expresses.gene(cds, \"egl-20\")))"
   ]
  },
  {

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Use case 4: re-clustering subsets of the data using t-SNE\n",
    "\n",
    "In the Cao et al. paper, we found that several of the neuron t-SNE clusters expressed markers of cholinergic neurons such as *unc-17*, *cho-1*, and *cha-1*. Let's perform a sub-clustering of these cholinergic neurons to see if we can get better separation. First, we'll identify which clusters are enriched for cells that express cholinergic markers."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": true
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "pData(cds.neurons)$any.cholinergic.marker =\n",
    "    (expresses.gene(cds.neurons, \"unc-17\") +\n",
    "     expresses.gene(cds.neurons, \"cho-1\") +\n",
    "     expresses.gene(cds.neurons, \"cha-1\")) > 0"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false

   "source": [
    "pData(cds.neurons) %>%\n",
    "    group_by(Cluster) %>%\n",
    "    summarize(\n",
    "        n.total = n(), n.cholinergic = sum(any.cholinergic.marker),\n",
    "        prop.cholinergic = n.cholinergic / n.total) %>%\n",
    "    inner_join(\n",
    "        unique(pData(cds.neurons)[, c(\"Cluster\", \"neuron.type\")]),\n",
    "        by = \"Cluster\") %>%\n",
    "    arrange(-prop.cholinergic) %>%\n",
    "    head(15)"
   ]

    "Now we'll cluster the cells in the t-SNE space using density peak clustering. In density peak clustering, `rho` measures to the local density of cells and `delta` measures the minimum distance to a region of higher local density. See http://science.sciencemag.org/content/344/6191/1492 for more details. You want to set thresholds on rho and delta that enclose the outlier points in the scatter plot. In my experience, it's usually better to over-cluster than to under-cluster."

   "source": [
    "DEG.results = lapply(cholinergic.clusters, function(this.cluster) {\n",
    "    message(\"Finding markers for cluster \", this.cluster)\n",
    "    cbind(\n",
    "        two.set.differential.gene.test(\n",
    "            cds.cholinergic,\n",
    "            pData(cds.cholinergic)$Cluster == this.cluster,\n",
    "            pData(cds.cholinergic)$Cluster != this.cluster),\n",
    "        data.frame(cluster = this.cluster))\n",
    "})"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 38,

    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "cholinergic.cluster.markers = do.call(rbind, DEG.results) %>% filter(higher.expr == \"Set 1\") %>%\n",
    "    select(\n",
    "        cluster, gene,\n",
    "        cluster.n.umi = set.1.n.umi,\n",
    "        other.n.umi = set.2.n.umi,\n",
    "        cluster.tpm = set.1.tpm,\n",
    "        other.tpm = set.2.tpm,\n",
    "        log2.ratio, precision, recall, f.score) %>%\n",
    "    arrange(-f.score)"
   ]
